*Nikola Dimitrijevic*  [6:44 AM]
Hey all, I wanted to open up a thread here to discuss about changes coming to gateway which we have to follow through on our own frontend repos, in this specific case for hub. Change coming up is related to auth token TTL, it will be 12 hours and users will have to be redirected to SSO to login page (there is currently a bug on heartbeat team or sso team that will force users to relog even if they have checked “Stay signed in” checkbox, but that’s another topic), to follow this change through on our end we have to properly handle 401 errors on our frontend’s side, as those 401 errors will be coming straight from gateway, they won’t be reaching our APIs backend servers. There are a couple of implementation challenges how to handle this while ensuring reliable 401 redirects to SSO and maintaining code readability, and easier code maintenance:
We attempted to reuse the existing expired token redirection logic on shell, previously implemented by Hosting team <https://github.com/gdcorp-partners/hcx-spa-shell/pull/147/files|here>. However, it doesn’t fully meet our needs because the redirection to SSO only occurs after a full page reload when the shell is called. This creates a problem where the token may expire, API calls start failing, but the user isn’t redirected to sso until they manually reload the page. Not sure if it would be the similar situation on Hosting as well?
Potential solutions we’re considering:
•  Implement a Service Worker in the shell to intercept 401 responses and trigger a redirect to SSO. This is our preferred solution, but it requires additional investigation and testing effort to set up properly.
•  Override axios and fetch globally and enforce the use of these instances across all SPAs to handle 401 responses consistently.
Do you have any suggestions or alternative ideas? This issue is affecting multiple teams and needs a global solution. (edited)

*Nikola Tucaković*  [6:59 AM]
for the short term, as we discussed, I’d suggest spinning up a SW which intercepts all requests and redirects to SSO page and that’s it.

Long term, high level, I think it’d be best for SSO team to provide a service worker (or a script to inject into service worker), which does basically the same thing, but also encompasses inline SSO login screen for better UX, without users having to leave the page they’re on.

If after such login we follow with a page reload, everything should work, user would stay put and that’s it. Downside could be for the pages/flows that aren’t persisting UI into url (like a modal modal where the error occurred not getting opened after reload or similar)

I’m just hoping there’s some proprietary in-house package already that would resolve this elegantly for us that I’m not aware of (edited)

*Nick Thomas*  [7:05 AM]
That direction sounds reasonable, especially for GET flows where the UX hit is low. One thing I wanted to flag for further discussion — how do we envision handling `POST` or `PUT` requests that fail with a `401`, especially in flows that involve side effects (like form submissions or actions via buttons)?
If the Service Worker intercepts and redirects immediately, we risk losing request body context. Do we plan to differentiate handling between safe (GET) and unsafe (POST/PUT) methods in the short term?

*Nikola Tucaković*  [7:10 AM]
that’s a very important point. I think it’s a fairly lower chance of errors popping up on a POST request vs GET request, just because of number of made GET vs POST.

I’m unsure how we could avoid losing context? It does sound super annoying for a long form to lose content because of a page reload (or for instance working out a client report in the Hub :sweat_smile:).

How about a warning modal that pops up once we detect a TTL issue? With a user action to do a reload (which will do  an SSO redirect) or dismiss a modal.

That way, user has a chance to copy whatever progress they made before having to reload the page and login? (edited)

*Ivan Marojevic*  [2:59 AM]
Hey, Team! Decided to post here since we all copy and paste a JWT at least 20 times a day :smile:
With the current security push, the Security Experience has been bolstering our applications in order to ensure a smoother transition to the API Gateway for our dependencies. For one of the initiatives, we found ourselves in a need for aging JWT tokens, to be able to test enforcing a redirect to SSO if a token had been issued more than 12h ago.
Here's a quick summary of what you need:

• Registering a client cert with SSO - this document sums it up pretty well. We used a pre-existing client cert in order to avoid unnecessary clutter.
    ◦ <https://godaddy-corp.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/AUTH/pages/89657340/Client+Certs#ClientCerts-RegisteryourcertwithSSO|Registering a client cert with SSO>
    ◦ The output from this should be a Registration workflow on the #sso-support channel, here's an example:
        ▪︎ <https://godaddy.slack.com/archives/C02AH2BUCVB/p1752083876675169?thread_ts=1752064718.858849&cid=C02AH2BUCVB|SSO Certificate Registration Workflow Example>
• 
• Now that cert can be used with SSO API in order to age the certificate, this guide is pretty straightforward:
    ◦ <https://godaddy-corp.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/AUTH/pages/89657501/Token+aging+service|Token Aging Service>
With these tools, there's no need to wait for anything when testing JWTs anymore, I hope you find this helpful! :time-travel:
